PiperOrigin-RevId: 382168291
Change-Id: Ia462f38030464fdd71a36f7b23c31066317216e4","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/abhilash1910/tensorflow/commits/4214a7e93beea7488250353deab124acdb0e1bba"},{"sha":"f37824765d77abae89f6ab106c3fe7228198b748","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Do not unroll concat HLO

Concatenation creates many IF- statements, and those tend to perform horribly
on GPU when unrolled, often resulting in excessive register spilling.

Makes BERT step ~16% faster.

On the following synthethic benchmark (simplest possible fusion involving concat):

```
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import sys

def main(n):
  print("""
HloModule module

ENTRY computation {
""")
  for i in range(n):
    print("p%s = f32[1000] parameter(%s)" % (i,i,))
    print("converted%s = f16[1000] convert(p%s)" % (i,i,))
  print("ROOT out = f16[%s] concatenate(" % (n * 1000)),
  for i in range(n):
    print("f16[1000] converted%s" % i),
    if i != n - 1:
      print(", "),
  print("), dimensions={0}")
  print("}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
  main(int(sys.argv[1]))
```

we see ~10% speed-up for n=10, and the speed-up grows to ~50% for n=100.

Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Refactor "reappear" logic into its own traversal (#21898)

When a Suspense boundary switches to its fallback state — or similarly,
when an Offscreen boundary switches from visible to hidden — we unmount
all its layout effects. When it resolves — or when Offscreen switches
back to visible — we mount them again. This "reappearing" logic
currently happens in the same commit phase traversal where we perform
normal layout effects.

I've changed it so that the "reappear" logic happens in its own
recurisve traversal that is separate from the commit phase one.

In the next step, I will do the same for the "disappear" logic that
currently lives in the `hideOrUnhideAllChildren` function.

There are a few reasons to model it this way, related to future
Offscreen features that we have planned. For example, we intend to
provide an imperative API to "appear" and "reappear" all the effects
within an Offscreen boundary. This API would be called from outside the
commit phase, during an arbitrary event. Which means it can't rely on
the regular commit phase — it's not part of a commit. This isn't the
only motivation but it illustrates why the separation makes sense.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/reez12g/react/commits/34600f4fadf526028a21c94030510fbed20e4665"},{"sha":"262ff7ad2c4a018de9992731fcf8a8f9c91083d8","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Refactor "disappear" logic into its own traversal (#21901)

Similar to #21898, but for "disappear" logic. Previously this lived
inside `hideOrUnhideAllChildren`, the function that mutates the nearest
DOM nodes to override their `display` style.

This makes the feature work in persistent mode (Fabric); it didn't
before because `hideOrUnhideAllChildren` only runs in mutation mode.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/reez12g/react/commits/262ff7ad2c4a018de9992731fcf8a8f9c91083d8"}]

[{"sha":"310187264d01a31bc3079358f13662d31a079d9e","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Clean up flushSync flow types (#21887)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sanketshah19/react/commits/310187264d01a31bc3079358f13662d31a079d9e"},{"sha":"34600f4fadf526028a21c94030510fbed20e4665","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Refactor "reappear" logic into its own traversal (#21898)

When a Suspense boundary switches to its fallback state — or similarly,
when an Offscreen boundary switches from visible to hidden — we unmount
all its layout effects. When it resolves — or when Offscreen switches
back to visible — we mount them again. This "reappearing" logic
currently happens in the same commit phase traversal where we perform
normal layout effects.

I've changed it so that the "reappear" logic happens in its own
recurisve traversal that is separate from the commit phase one.

In the next step, I will do the same for the "disappear" logic that
currently lives in the `hideOrUnhideAllChildren` function.

There are a few reasons to model it this way, related to future
Offscreen features that we have planned. For example, we intend to
provide an imperative API to "appear" and "reappear" all the effects
within an Offscreen boundary. This API would be called from outside the
commit phase, during an arbitrary event. Which means it can't rely on
the regular commit phase — it's not part of a commit. This isn't the
only motivation but it illustrates why the separation makes sense.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sanketshah19/react/commits/34600f4fadf526028a21c94030510fbed20e4665"},{"sha":"262ff7ad2c4a018de9992731fcf8a8f9c91083d8","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Refactor "disappear" logic into its own traversal (#21901)

Similar to #21898, but for "disappear" logic. Previously this lived
inside `hideOrUnhideAllChildren`, the function that mutates the nearest
DOM nodes to override their `display` style.

This makes the feature work in persistent mode (Fabric); it didn't
before because `hideOrUnhideAllChildren` only runs in mutation mode.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sanketshah19/react/commits/262ff7ad2c4a018de9992731fcf8a8f9c91083d8"}]

Now we handle ops with `MemoryEffectOpInterface` less conservative which makes
side-effect analysis more efficient. In particular, for a resource-allocating op
with empty or anonymous `shared_name` attribute we can assume that the resource
being created is unique which wasn't utilized before. One implication of this is
less control dependencies in the exported GraphDef.
Also added tests and improved some comments.

[{"sha":"310187264d01a31bc3079358f13662d31a079d9e","author":{"name":"Ricky","email":"7d12b144c45a90369c62925ec4a27c43a68a93bf@gmail.com"},"message":"Clean up flushSync flow types (#21887)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/react/commits/310187264d01a31bc3079358f13662d31a079d9e"},{"sha":"34600f4fadf526028a21c94030510fbed20e4665","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Refactor "reappear" logic into its own traversal (#21898)

When a Suspense boundary switches to its fallback state — or similarly,
when an Offscreen boundary switches from visible to hidden — we unmount
all its layout effects. When it resolves — or when Offscreen switches
back to visible — we mount them again. This "reappearing" logic
currently happens in the same commit phase traversal where we perform
normal layout effects.

I've changed it so that the "reappear" logic happens in its own
recurisve traversal that is separate from the commit phase one.

In the next step, I will do the same for the "disappear" logic that
currently lives in the `hideOrUnhideAllChildren` function.

There are a few reasons to model it this way, related to future
Offscreen features that we have planned. For example, we intend to
provide an imperative API to "appear" and "reappear" all the effects
within an Offscreen boundary. This API would be called from outside the
commit phase, during an arbitrary event. Which means it can't rely on
the regular commit phase — it's not part of a commit. This isn't the
only motivation but it illustrates why the separation makes sense.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/react/commits/34600f4fadf526028a21c94030510fbed20e4665"},{"sha":"262ff7ad2c4a018de9992731fcf8a8f9c91083d8","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Refactor "disappear" logic into its own traversal (#21901)

Similar to #21898, but for "disappear" logic. Previously this lived
inside `hideOrUnhideAllChildren`, the function that mutates the nearest
DOM nodes to override their `display` style.

This makes the feature work in persistent mode (Fabric); it didn't
before because `hideOrUnhideAllChildren` only runs in mutation mode.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sthagen/react/commits/262ff7ad2c4a018de9992731fcf8a8f9c91083d8"},{"sha":"bdc4be6c575d4c5822adba3bd271d1e0e6d2a3ce","author":{"name":"Stefan Hagen","email":"eb0877843acc39f8ef6f7269937dee931c372d23@hagen.link"},"message":"Merge pull request #57 from facebook/main

Concatenation creates many IF- statements, and those tend to perform horribly
on GPU when unrolled, often resulting in excessive register spilling.

Makes BERT step ~16% faster.

On the following synthethic benchmark (simplest possible fusion involving concat):

```
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import sys

def main(n):
  print("""
HloModule module

ENTRY computation {
""")
  for i in range(n):
    print("p%s = f32[1000] parameter(%s)" % (i,i,))
    print("converted%s = f16[1000] convert(p%s)" % (i,i,))
  print("ROOT out = f16[%s] concatenate(" % (n * 1000)),
  for i in range(n):
    print("f16[1000] converted%s" % i),
    if i != n - 1:
      print(", "),
  print("), dimensions={0}")
  print("}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
  main(int(sys.argv[1]))
```

we see ~10% speed-up for n=10, and the speed-up grows to ~50% for n=100.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 382168291
Change-Id: Ia462f38030464fdd71a36f7b23c31066317216e4","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/alexsnow348/tensorflow/commits/4214a7e93beea7488250353deab124acdb0e1bba"},{"sha":"f37824765d77abae89f6ab106c3fe7228198b748","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Do not unroll concat HLO

Concatenation creates many IF- statements, and those tend to perform horribly
on GPU when unrolled, often resulting in excessive register spilling.

Makes BERT step ~16% faster.

On the following synthethic benchmark (simplest possible fusion involving concat):

```
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import sys

def main(n):
  print("""
HloModule module

ENTRY computation {
""")
  for i in range(n):
    print("p%s = f32[1000] parameter(%s)" % (i,i,))
    print("converted%s = f16[1000] convert(p%s)" % (i,i,))
  print("ROOT out = f16[%s] concatenate(" % (n * 1000)),
  for i in range(n):
    print("f16[1000] converted%s" % i),
    if i != n - 1:
      print(", "),
  print("), dimensions={0}")
  print("}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
  main(int(sys.argv[1]))
```

we see ~10% speed-up for n=10, and the speed-up grows to ~50% for n=100.

the setting from the external environment. However, "kumactl install"

explictly. Update the remaining uses so that "kumactl install" always
targets the correct test cluster.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 382168291
Change-Id: Ia462f38030464fdd71a36f7b23c31066317216e4","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NamWoo/tensorflow/commits/4214a7e93beea7488250353deab124acdb0e1bba"},{"sha":"f37824765d77abae89f6ab106c3fe7228198b748","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Do not unroll concat HLO

Concatenation creates many IF- statements, and those tend to perform horribly
on GPU when unrolled, often resulting in excessive register spilling.

Makes BERT step ~16% faster.

On the following synthethic benchmark (simplest possible fusion involving concat):

```
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import sys

def main(n):
  print("""
HloModule module

ENTRY computation {
""")
  for i in range(n):
    print("p%s = f32[1000] parameter(%s)" % (i,i,))
    print("converted%s = f16[1000] convert(p%s)" % (i,i,))
  print("ROOT out = f16[%s] concatenate(" % (n * 1000)),
  for i in range(n):
    print("f16[1000] converted%s" % i),
    if i != n - 1:
      print(", "),
  print("), dimensions={0}")
  print("}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
  main(int(sys.argv[1]))
```

we see ~10% speed-up for n=10, and the speed-up grows to ~50% for n=100.
